lenders.loan_because:
I loan because I’m utterly passionate about humanity and what we can all do with what we’re given.

The first few times as a child when I met people who needed money more than I did at the moment, I wanted to give them everything I had – which is neither realistic nor attainable if I also want to enjoy my own life, as well as keep both giving and loaning over the years!  I’m a struggling student now, but as I become savvier and wealthier I hope to be able to do more.

So I do what I can for those who are clearly trying.  I buy new kitchen supplies for shelters in my area, I donate regularly to a few of the food and animal charities closest to my heart, and I loan on Kiva to wonderful people trying to make their own difference in the world of food!

lenders.loan_because: My incredibly gracious mother bought a Kiva certificate for me as a gift and opened the door to this website in my life. I've been reloaning whatever money I can since. Although it isn't much money I can spare, I know that many small collaborative efforts can combine to make life-changing differences in peoples' lives, particularly those not as privileged as myself. This is why I loan. To make a difference.
lenders.occupational_info: I'm a student at Michigan State University studying human biology with intentions of becoming a health professional and possibly conducting research to make a new discovery in my field of specialty that I choose. I've always lived in the United States which automatically shields me from a lot of the way the world works, which I find unfortunate, yet I still strive to learn as much as I can outside of my own cultural veils that distort my understanding and observations, and help in any way that I can, although I have my own agenda which keeps me extremely busy, which is also unfortunate. I think it's absolutely wrong that people in my country live in such luxury and maintain an ignorance and apathetic view of their brothers and sisters overseas. Mankind must unite if we ever hope to balance the immense disparities that exist in our world, and to overcome immense global issues such as disease epidemics, global warming, and seemingly an unstoppable use of finite resources from our planet to meet demands of a never-quenched materialistic hunger.
